[src:hypothesis-property/edge-case] An **edge case** is a problem or situation that occurs only at an extreme (maximum or minimum) operating parameter.
[src:hypothesis-property/edge-case] For example, a stereo speaker might noticeably distort audio when played at maximum volume, even in the absence of any other extreme setting or condition.
[src:hypothesis-property/edge-case] An edge case can be expected or unexpected.
[src:hypothesis-property/edge-case] In engineering, the process of planning for and gracefully addressing edge cases can be a significant task, and yet this task may be overlooked or underestimated.
[src:hypothesis-property/edge-case] Non-trivial edge cases can result in the failure of an object that is being engineered.
[src:hypothesis-property/edge-case] They may not have been foreseen during the design phase, and they may not have been thought possible during normal use of the object.
[src:hypothesis-property/edge-case] For this reason, attempts to formalize good engineering standards often include information about edge cases.
[src:hypothesis-property/edge-case] In programming, an edge case typically involves input values that require special handling in an algorithm behind a computer program.
[src:hypothesis-property/edge-case] As a measure for validating the behavior of computer programs in such cases, unit tests are usually created; they are testing boundary conditions of an algorithm, function or method.
[src:hypothesis-property/edge-case] A series of edge cases around each "boundary" can be used to give reasonable coverage and confidence using the assumption that if it behaves correctly at the edges, it should behave everywhere else.
[src:hypothesis-property/edge-case] For example, a function that divides two numbers might be tested using both very large and very small numbers.
[src:hypothesis-property/edge-case] This assumes that if it works for both ends of the magnitude spectrum, it should work correctly in between.
[src:hypothesis-property/edge-case] Programmers may also create integration tests to address edge cases not covered by unit tests.
[src:hypothesis-property/edge-case] These tests cover cases which only appear when a system is tested as a whole.
[src:hypothesis-property/edge-case] For example, while a unit test may ensure that a function correctly calculates a result, an integration test ensures that this function works properly when integrated with a database or an external API.
[src:hypothesis-property/edge-case] These tests are particularly relevant with increasing system complexity in distributed systems, microservices, and Internet of things (IoT) devices.
[src:hypothesis-property/edge-case] With microservices in particular, testing becomes a challenge as integration tests may not cover all microservice endpoints, resulting in uncovered edge cases.
[src:hypothesis-property/edge-case] Other types of testing which relate to edge cases may include load testing and negative/failure testing.
[src:hypothesis-property/edge-case] Both methods aim at expanding the test coverage of a system, reducing the likelihood of unexpected edge cases.
[src:hypothesis-property/edge-case] In test-driven development, edge cases may be determined by system requirements and accounted for by tests, before writing code.
[src:hypothesis-property/edge-case] Such documentation may go inside a product requirements document after discussions with stakeholders and other teams.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] In programming and software development, **fuzzing** or **fuzz testing** is an automated software testing technique that involves providing invalid, unexpected, or random data as inputs to a computer program.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] The program is then monitored for exceptions such as crashes, failing built-in code assertions, or potential memory leaks.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Typically, fuzzers are used to test programs that take structured inputs.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] This structure is specified, such as in a file format or protocol and distinguishes valid from invalid input.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] An effective fuzzer generates semi-valid inputs that are "valid enough" in that they are not directly rejected by the parser, but do create unexpected behaviors deeper in the program and are "invalid enough" to expose corner cases that have not been properly dealt with.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] For the purpose of security, input that crosses a trust boundary is often the most useful.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] For example, it is more important to fuzz code that handles a file uploaded by any user than it is to fuzz the code that parses a configuration file that is accessible only to a privileged user.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] The term "fuzz" originates from a 1988 class project in the graduate Advanced Operating Systems class (CS736), taught by Prof.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Barton Miller at the University of Wisconsin, whose results were subsequently published in 1990.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] To fuzz test a UNIX utility meant to automatically generate random input and command-line parameters for the utility.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] The project was designed to test the reliability of UNIX command line programs by executing a large number of random inputs in quick succession until they crashed.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Miller's team was able to crash 25 to 33 percent of the utilities that they tested.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] They then debugged each of the crashes to determine the cause and categorized each detected failure.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] To allow other researchers to conduct similar experiments with other software, the source code of the tools, the test procedures, and the raw result data were made publicly available.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] This early fuzzing would now be called black box, generational, unstructured (dumb or "classic") fuzzing.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Barton Miller, "In the process of writing the project description, I needed to give this kind of testing a name.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] I wanted a name that would evoke the feeling of random, unstructured data.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] A key contribution of this early work was simple (almost simplistic) oracle.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] A program failed its test if it crashed or hung under the random input and was considered to have passed otherwise.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] While test oracles can be challenging to construct, the oracle for this early fuzz testing was simple and universal to apply.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] In April 2012, Google announced ClusterFuzz, a cloud-based fuzzing infrastructure for security-critical components of the Chromium web browser.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Security researchers can upload their own fuzzers and collect bug bounties if ClusterFuzz finds a crash with the uploaded fuzzer.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] In September 2014, Shellshock was disclosed as a family of security bugs in the widely used UNIX Bash shell; most vulnerabilities of Shellshock were found using the fuzzer AFL.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] (Many Internet-facing services, such as some web server deployments, use Bash to process certain requests, allowing an attacker to cause vulnerable versions of Bash to execute arbitrary commands.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] In April 2015, Hanno Böck showed how the fuzzer AFL could have found the 2014 Heartbleed vulnerability.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] (The Heartbleed vulnerability was disclosed in April 2014.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] It is a serious vulnerability that allows adversaries to decipher otherwise encrypted communication.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] The vulnerability was accidentally introduced into OpenSSL which implements TLS and is used by the majority of the servers on the internet.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] In August 2016, the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) held the finals of the first Cyber Grand Challenge, a fully automated capture-the-flag competition that lasted 11 hours.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] The objective was to develop automatic defense systems that can discover, exploit, and correct software flaws in real-time.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Fuzzing was used as an effective offense strategy to discover flaws in the software of the opponents.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] It showed tremendous potential in the automation of vulnerability detection.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] The winner was a system called "Mayhem" developed by the team ForAllSecure led by David Brumley.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] In September 2016, Microsoft announced Project Springfield, a cloud-based fuzz testing service for finding security critical bugs in software.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] In December 2016, Google announced OSS-Fuzz which allows for continuous fuzzing of several security-critical open-source projects.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] At Black Hat 2018, Christopher Domas demonstrated the use of fuzzing to expose the existence of a hidden RISC core in a processor.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] This core was able to bypass existing security checks to execute Ring 0 commands from Ring 3.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] In September 2020, Microsoft released OneFuzz, a self-hosted fuzzing-as-a-service platform that automates the detection of software bugs.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] It was archived three years later on November 1, 2023.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Testing programs with random inputs dates back to the 1950s when data was still stored on punched cards.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Programmers would use punched cards that were pulled from the trash or card decks of random numbers as input to computer programs.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] If an execution revealed undesired behavior, a bug had been detected.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] The execution of random inputs is also called random testing, monkey testing or Monte Carlo debugging (in analogy to Monte Carlo methods).
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] In 1981, Duran and Ntafos formally investigated the effectiveness of testing a program with random inputs.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] While random testing had been widely perceived to be the worst means of testing a program, the authors could show that it is a cost-effective alternative to more systematic testing techniques.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] In 1983, Steve Capps at Apple developed "The Monkey", a tool that would generate random inputs for classic Mac OS applications, such as MacPaint.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] The figurative "monkey" refers to the infinite monkey theorem which states that a monkey hitting keys at random on a typewriter keyboard for an infinite amount of time will eventually type out the entire works of Shakespeare.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] In the case of testing, the monkey would write the particular sequence of inputs that would trigger a crash.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] In 1991, the crashme tool was released, which was intended to test the robustness of Unix and Unix-like operating systems by randomly executing systems calls with randomly chosen parameters.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] A fuzzer can be dumb (unstructured) or smart (structured) depending on whether it is aware of input structure.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] A fuzzer can be white-, grey-, or black-box, depending on whether it is aware of program structure.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] A mutation-based fuzzer leverages an existing corpus of seed inputs during fuzzing.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] It generates inputs by modifying (or rather mutating) the provided seeds.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] For example, when fuzzing the image library libpng, the user would provide a set of valid PNG image files as seeds while a mutation-based fuzzer would modify these seeds to produce semi-valid variants of each seed.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] The corpus of seed files may contain thousands of potentially similar inputs.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Automated seed selection (or test suite reduction) allows users to pick the best seeds in order to maximize the total number of bugs found during a fuzz campaign.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] A generation-based fuzzer generates inputs from scratch.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] For instance, a smart generation-based fuzzer takes the input model that was provided by the user to generate new inputs.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Unlike mutation-based fuzzers, a generation-based fuzzer does not depend on the existence or quality of a corpus of seed inputs.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Some fuzzers have the capability to do both, to generate inputs from scratch and to generate inputs by mutation of existing seeds.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Typically, fuzzers are used to generate inputs for programs that take structured inputs, such as a file, a sequence of keyboard or mouse events, or a sequence of messages.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] This structure distinguishes valid input that is accepted and processed by the program from invalid input that is quickly rejected by the program.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] What constitutes a valid input may be explicitly specified in an input model.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Examples of input models are formal grammars, file formats, GUI-models, and network protocols.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Even items not normally considered as input can be fuzzed, such as the contents of databases, shared memory, environment variables or the precise interleaving of threads.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] An effective fuzzer generates semi-valid inputs that are "valid enough" so that they are not directly rejected from the parser and "invalid enough" so that they might stress corner cases and exercise interesting program behaviours.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] A smart (model-based, grammar-based, or protocol-based) fuzzer leverages the input model to generate a greater proportion of valid inputs.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] For instance, if the input can be modelled as an abstract syntax tree, then a smart mutation-based fuzzer would employ random transformations to move complete subtrees from one node to another.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] If the input can be modelled by a formal grammar, a smart generation-based fuzzer would instantiate the production rules to generate inputs that are valid with respect to the grammar.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] However, generally the input model must be explicitly provided, which is difficult to do when the model is proprietary, unknown, or very complex.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] If a large corpus of valid and invalid inputs is available, a grammar induction technique, such as Angluin's L* algorithm, would be able to generate an input model.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] A dumb fuzzer does not require the input model and can thus be employed to fuzz a wider variety of programs.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] For instance, AFL is a dumb mutation-based fuzzer that modifies a seed file by flipping random bits, by substituting random bytes with "interesting" values, and by moving or deleting blocks of data.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] However, a dumb fuzzer might generate a lower proportion of valid inputs and stress the parser code rather than the main components of a program.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] The disadvantage of dumb fuzzers can be illustrated by means of the construction of a valid checksum for a cyclic redundancy check (CRC).
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] A CRC is an error-detecting code that ensures that the integrity of the data contained in the input file is preserved during transmission.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] A checksum is computed over the input data and recorded in the file.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] When the program processes the received file and the recorded checksum does not match the re-computed checksum, then the file is rejected as invalid.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Now, a fuzzer that is unaware of the CRC is unlikely to generate the correct checksum.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] However, there are attempts to identify and re-compute a potential checksum in the mutated input, once a dumb mutation-based fuzzer has modified the protected data.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Typically, a fuzzer is considered more effective if it achieves a higher degree of code coverage.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] The rationale is, if a fuzzer does not exercise certain structural elements in the program, then it is also not able to reveal bugs that are hiding in these elements.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Some program elements are considered more critical than others.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] For instance, a division operator might cause a division by zero error, or a system call may crash the program.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] A black-box fuzzer treats the program as a black box and is unaware of internal program structure.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] For instance, a random testing tool that generates inputs at random is considered a blackbox fuzzer.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Hence, a blackbox fuzzer can execute several hundred inputs per second, can be easily parallelized, and can scale to programs of arbitrary size.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] However, blackbox fuzzers may only scratch the surface and expose "shallow" bugs.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Hence, there are attempts to develop blackbox fuzzers that can incrementally learn about the internal structure (and behavior) of a program during fuzzing by observing the program's output given an input.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] For instance, LearnLib employs active learning to generate an automaton that represents the behavior of a web application.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] A white-box fuzzer leverages program analysis to systematically increase code coverage or to reach certain critical program locations.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] For instance, SAGE leverages symbolic execution to systematically explore different paths in the program (a technique known as concolic execution).
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] If the program's specification is available, a whitebox fuzzer might leverage techniques from model-based testing to generate inputs and check the program outputs against the program specification.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] A whitebox fuzzer can be very effective at exposing bugs that hide deep in the program.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] However, the time used for analysis (of the program or its specification) can become prohibitive.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] If the whitebox fuzzer takes relatively too long to generate an input, a blackbox fuzzer will be more efficient.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Hence, there are attempts to combine the efficiency of blackbox fuzzers and the effectiveness of whitebox fuzzers.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] A gray-box fuzzer leverages instrumentation rather than program analysis to glean information about the program.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] For instance, AFL and libFuzzer utilize lightweight instrumentation to trace basic block transitions exercised by an input.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] This leads to a reasonable performance overhead but informs the fuzzer about the increase in code coverage during fuzzing, which makes gray-box fuzzers extremely efficient vulnerability detection tools.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Fuzzing is used mostly as an automated technique to expose vulnerabilities in security-critical programs that might be exploited with malicious intent.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] More generally, fuzzing is used to demonstrate the presence of bugs rather than their absence.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Running a fuzzing campaign for several weeks without finding a bug does not prove the program correct.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] After all, the program may still fail for an input that has not been executed, yet; executing a program for all inputs is prohibitively expensive.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] If the objective is to prove a program correct for all inputs, a formal specification must exist and techniques from formal methods must be used.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] In order to expose bugs, a fuzzer must be able to distinguish expected (normal) from unexpected (buggy) program behavior.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] However, a machine cannot always distinguish a bug from a feature.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] In automated software testing, this is also called the test oracle problem.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Typically, a fuzzer distinguishes between crashing and non-crashing inputs in the absence of specifications and to use a simple and objective measure.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Crashes can be easily identified and might indicate potential vulnerabilities (e.g., denial of service or arbitrary code execution).
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] However, the absence of a crash does not indicate the absence of a vulnerability.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] For instance, a program written in C may or may not crash when an input causes a buffer overflow.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Rather the program's behavior is undefined.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] To make a fuzzer more sensitive to failures other than crashes, sanitizers can be used to inject assertions that crash the program when a failure is detected.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Fuzzing can also be used to detect "differential" bugs if a reference implementation is available.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] For automated regression testing, the generated inputs are executed on two versions of the same program.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] For automated differential testing, the generated inputs are executed on two implementations of the same program (e.g., lighttpd and httpd are both implementations of a web server).
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] If the two variants produce different output for the same input, then one may be buggy and should be examined more closely.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Static program analysis analyzes a program without actually executing it.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] This might lead to false positives where the tool reports problems with the program that do not actually exist.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Fuzzing in combination with dynamic program analysis can be used to try to generate an input that actually witnesses the reported problem.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Modern web browsers undergo extensive fuzzing.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] The Chromium code of Google Chrome is continuously fuzzed by the Chrome Security Team with 15,000 cores.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] For Microsoft Edge [Legacy] and Internet Explorer, Microsoft performed fuzzed testing with 670 machine-years during product development, generating more than 400 billion DOM manipulations from 1 billion HTML files.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] A fuzzer produces a large number of inputs in a relatively short time.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] For instance, in 2016 the Google OSS-fuzz project produced around 4 trillion inputs a week.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Hence, many fuzzers provide a toolchain that automates otherwise manual and tedious tasks which follow the automated generation of failure-inducing inputs.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Automated bug triage is used to group a large number of failure-inducing inputs by root cause and to prioritize each individual bug by severity.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] A fuzzer produces a large number of inputs, and many of the failure-inducing ones may effectively expose the same software bug.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Only some of these bugs are security-critical and should be patched with higher priority.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] For instance the CERT Coordination Center provides the Linux triage tools which group crashing inputs by the produced stack trace and lists each group according to their probability to be exploitable.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Previously unreported, triaged bugs might be automatically reported to a bug tracking system.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] For instance, OSS-Fuzz runs large-scale, long-running fuzzing campaigns for several security-critical software projects where each previously unreported, distinct bug is reported directly to a bug tracker.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] The OSS-Fuzz bug tracker automatically informs the maintainer of the vulnerable software and checks in regular intervals whether the bug has been fixed in the most recent revision using the uploaded minimized failure-inducing input.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Automated input minimization (or test case reduction) is an automated debugging technique to isolate that part of the failure-inducing input that is actually inducing the failure.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] If the failure-inducing input is large and mostly malformed, it might be difficult for a developer to understand what exactly is causing the bug.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] Given the failure-inducing input, an automated minimization tool would remove as many input bytes as possible while still reproducing the original bug.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] For instance, Delta Debugging is an automated input minimization technique that employs an extended binary search algorithm to find such a minimal input.
[src:hypothesis-property/fuzzing] The following is a list of fuzzers described as "popular", "widely used", or similar in the academic literature.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] A *property testing algorithm* for a decision problem is an algorithm whose query complexity (the number of queries made to its input) is much smaller than the instance size of the problem.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] Property testing algorithms are central to the definition of probabilistically checkable proofs, as a probabilistically checkable proof is essentially a proof that can be verified by a property testing algorithm.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] Here, "x is ε-far from L" means that the Hamming distance between x and any string in L is at least *ε* |*x*|.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] A property testing algorithm is said to have *one-sided error* if it satisfies the stronger condition that the accepting probability for instances *x* ∈ *L* is 1 instead of 2/3.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] A property testing algorithm is said be *non-adaptive* if it performs all its queries before it "observes" any answers to previous queries.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] Such an algorithm can be viewed as operating in the following manner.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] Before looking at the input, using its internal randomness, the algorithm decides which symbols of the input are to be queried.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] Next, the algorithm observes these symbols.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] Finally, without making any additional queries (but possibly using its randomness), the algorithm decides whether to accept or reject the input.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] The main efficiency parameter of a property testing algorithm is its query complexity, which is the maximum number of input symbols inspected over all inputs of a given length (and all random choices made by the algorithm).
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] Computer scientists are interested in designing algorithms whose query complexity is as small as possible.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] In many cases, the running time of property testing algorithms is sublinear in the instance length.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] Typically, the goal is first to make the query complexity as small as possible as a function of the instance size n, and then study the dependency on the proximity parameter ε.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] Unlike other complexity-theoretic settings, the asymptotic query complexity of property testing algorithms is affected dramatically by the representation of instances.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] For example, when *ε* = 0.01, the problem of testing bipartiteness of *dense graphs* (which are represented by their adjacency matrix) admits an algorithm of constant query complexity.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] In contrast, sparse graphs on n vertices (which are represented by their adjacency list) require property testing algorithms of query complexity Ω(*n*1/2).
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] The query complexity of property testing algorithms grows as the proximity parameter ε becomes smaller for all non-trivial properties.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] This dependence on ε is necessary, as a change of fewer than ε symbols in the input cannot be detected with constant probability using fewer than *O*(1/*ε*) queries.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] Many interesting properties of dense graphs can be tested using query complexity that depends only on ε and not on the graph size n.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] However, the query complexity can grow enormously fast as a function of ε.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] For example, for a long time, the best known algorithm for testing whether a graph does not contain any triangle had a query complexity which is a tower function of poly(1/*ε*), and only in 2010 was this improved to a tower function of log(1/*ε*).
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] One of the reasons for this enormous growth in bounds is that many of the positive results for property testing of graphs are established using the Szemerédi regularity lemma, which also has tower-type bounds in its conclusions.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] The connection of property testing to the Szemerédi regularity lemma and related graph removal lemmas is elaborated on below.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] For a graph G with n vertices, the notion of distance we will use is the *edit distance*.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] That is, we say that the distance between two graphs is the smallest ε such that one can add and/or delete *εn*2 edges and get from the first graph to the second.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] Under a reasonable representation of graphs, this is equivalent to the earlier *Hamming distance* definition (up to possibly a change of constants).
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] To make precise the general notions of property testing in the context of graphs, we say a tester for graph property P should distinguish with at least two-thirds probability between the cases of G satisfying P and the cases where G is ε-far in edit distance from satisfying P.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] The tester can access some oracle to query whether a pair of vertices has an edge between them in G or not.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] The *query complexity* is the number of such oracle queries.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] Say the tester has *one-sided error* if it has false positives and not false negatives, i.e. if G satisfies P, the tester always outputs the correct answer.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] We can only differentiate between graphs that satisfy P versus those far from P, as opposed to satisfying versus not satisfying P.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] In the latter case, consider two graphs: G satisfying P and H not satisfying P by changing only a few edges.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] One example is testing triangle-freeness with *H* a graph with exactly one triangle and G having one of these edges removed.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] Then, the tester cannot tell them apart unless it queries every edge, which it cannot do.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] The field of graph property testing was first introduced by Goldreich, Goldwasser, and Ron.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] In their seminal paper published in 1998, an abstract graph partition problem is analyzed and some testers provided.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] These include as special cases several important graph properties like bipartiteness, *k*-colorability, having a large clique, and having a large cut.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] In particular, the *natural* algorithms that sample a subgraph and check whether it satisfy the property are all correct, albeit with perhaps-suboptimal query complexities.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] A graph property is *hereditary* if it is preserved under deletion of vertices, or equivalently, if it is preserved under taking induced subgraphs.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] A few important hereditary properties are *H*-freeness (for some graph *H*), k-colorability, and planarity.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] Every hereditary graph property is testable with one-sided error.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] The proof relies on a version of the **graph removal lemma** for infinite families of induced subgraphs.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] The query complexity using this regularity approach is large due to the tower function bound in the **Szemerédi regularity lemma**.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] Informally, an *oblivious tester* is oblivious to the size of the input.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] For a graph property P, it is an algorithm that takes as input a parameter ε and graph G, and then runs as a property testing algorithm on G for the property P with proximity parameter ε that makes exactly *q*(*ε*) queries to G.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] Crucially, the number of queries an oblivious tester makes is a constant dependent only on ε and not the size of the input graph G.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] In complete analogy with property testing algorithms, we can talk about oblivious testers with one-sided error.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] We can contrive some graph properties for which a tester must access the number of vertices.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] In this case, the tester cannot even differentiate which property (bipartiteness or perfectness) to test unless it knows the number of vertices.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] There are many examples of such unnatural properties.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] In fact, the characterization of graph properties testable by an oblivious tester with one-sided error leads to a class of natural properties.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] Trivially, hereditary properties are also semi-hereditary.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] This characterization partially answers the converse to the other Alon & Shapira theorem above: the properties that are easy to test properties (having oblivious testers with one-sided error) are almost hereditary.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] In this section, we will give some *natural* oblivious testing algorithms with one-sided error for triangle-freeness, bipartiteness, and k-colorability.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] They are natural in the sense that we follow the natural idea of randomly sampling some subset X of vertices of *G* and checking whether the graph property holds on the subgraph spanned by *X* by brute-force search.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] We have one-sided error since these properties are actually hereditary: if *G* satisfy the property, so must the induced subgraph spanned by *X*, so our tester always accepts.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] For triangle-freeness, the tester is an application of the **triangle removal lemma**.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] In particular, it tells us that if graph *G* is ε-far from being triangle-free, then there is a (computable) constant *δ* = *δ*(*ε*) so that G has at least *δn*3 triangles.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] For bipartiteness and k-colorability, let δ be the desired upper bound on error probability for the following testers.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] Note that query complexity should not be confused with running time.
[src:hypothesis-property/property-testing] The latter is often exponential (as is the case of both) due to a lack of polynomial time decision algorithm to test the property on the induced subgraph.
[src:hypothesis-property/quickcheck] It is compatible with the compiler, Glasgow Haskell Compiler (GHC) and the interpreter, Haskell User's Gofer System (Hugs).
[src:hypothesis-property/quickcheck] It is free and open-source software released under a BSD-style license.
[src:hypothesis-property/quickcheck] In QuickCheck, assertions are written about logical properties that a function should fulfill.
[src:hypothesis-property/quickcheck] Then QuickCheck attempts to generate a test case that falsifies such assertions.
[src:hypothesis-property/quickcheck] Once such a test case is found, QuickCheck tries to reduce it to a minimal failing subset by removing or simplifying input data that are unneeded to make the test fail.
[src:hypothesis-property/quickcheck] Besides being used to test regular programs, QuickCheck is also useful for building up a functional specification, for documenting what functions should be doing, and for testing compiler implementations.
[src:hypothesis-property/quickstart] This is a lightning introduction to the most important features of Hypothesis; enough to get you started writing tests.
[src:hypothesis-property/quickstart] The tutorial introduces these features (and more) in greater detail.
[src:hypothesis-property/quickstart] `@given` is the standard entrypoint to Hypothesis.
[src:hypothesis-property/quickstart] It takes a *strategy*, which describes the type of inputs you want the decorated function to accept.
[src:hypothesis-property/quickstart] When we call `test_integers`, Hypothesis will generate random integers (because we used the `integers()` strategy) and pass them as `n`.
[src:hypothesis-property/quickstart] We just called `test_integers()`, without passing a value for `n`, because Hypothesis generates random values of `n` for us.
[src:hypothesis-property/quickstart] By default, Hypothesis generates 100 random inputs.
[src:hypothesis-property/quickstart] You can control this with the `max_examples` setting.
[src:hypothesis-property/quickstart] A Hypothesis test is still a regular python function, which means pytest or unittest will pick it up and run it in all the normal ways.
[src:hypothesis-property/quickstart] See `@given` for details about how `@given` handles different types of arguments.
[src:hypothesis-property/quickstart] Sometimes, you need to remove invalid cases from your test.
[src:hypothesis-property/quickstart] You can learn more about `.filter()` and `assume()` in the Adapting strategies tutorial page.
[src:hypothesis-property/quickstart] You may want an input to depend on the value of another input.
[src:hypothesis-property/quickstart] For instance, you might want to generate two integers `n1` and `n2` where `n1 <= n2`.
[src:hypothesis-property/quickstart] You can do this using the `@composite` strategy.
[src:hypothesis-property/quickstart] `@composite` lets you define a new strategy which is itself built by drawing values from other strategies, using the automatically-passed `draw` function.
[src:hypothesis-property/quickstart] In more complex cases, you might need to interleave generation and test code.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Software testing can provide objective, independent information about the quality of software and the risk of its failure to a user or sponsor or any other stakeholder.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Software testing can determine the correctness of software for specific scenarios but cannot determine correctness for all scenarios.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Based on the criteria for measuring correctness from an oracle, software testing employs principles and mechanisms that might recognize a problem.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Examples of oracles include specifications, contracts, comparable products, past versions of the same product, inferences about intended or expected purpose, user or customer expectations, relevant standards, and applicable laws.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Software testing can be functional or non-functional in nature.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Software testing is often dynamic in nature: running the software to verify actual output matches expected.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] It can also be static in nature: reviewing code and its associated documentation.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Software testing is often used to answer the question: Does the software do what it is supposed to do and what it needs to do?
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Information learned from software testing may be used to improve the process by which software is developed.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] A commonly suggested approach to automated testing is the "test pyramid," wherein most of the tests are unit tests, followed by a smaller set of integration tests and finally a few end-to-end (e2e) tests.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] A study conducted by NIST in 2002 reported that software bugs cost the U.S. economy $59.5 billion annually.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] More than a third of this cost could be avoided if better software testing was performed.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Outsourcing software testing because of costs is very common, with China, the Philippines, India and Pakistan being preferred destinations.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Myers initially introduced the separation of debugging from testing in 1979.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Although his attention was on breakage testing ("A successful test case is one that detects an as-yet undiscovered error."), it illustrated the desire of the software engineering community to separate fundamental development activities, such as debugging, from that of verification.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Software testing typically includes handling software bugs – a defect in the code that causes an undesirable result.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Bugs generally slow testing progress and involve programmer assistance to debug and fix.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] For example, a defect in dead code will not be considered a failure.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] A defect that does not cause failure at one point in time may lead to failure later due to environmental changes.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Examples of environment change include running on new computer hardware, changes in data, and interacting with different software.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Software testing is typically goal driven.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] A single defect may result in multiple failure symptoms.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Software testing may involve a Requirements gap – omission from the design for a requirement.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Requirement gaps can often be non-functional requirements such as testability, scalability, maintainability, performance, and security.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] A fundamental limitation of software testing is that testing under *all* combinations of inputs and preconditions (initial state) is not feasible, even with a simple product.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Defects that manifest in unusual conditions are difficult to find in testing.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Also, non-functional dimensions of quality (how it is supposed to *be* versus what it is supposed to *do*) – usability, scalability, performance, compatibility, and reliability – can be subjective; something that constitutes sufficient value to one person may not to another.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Although testing for every possible input is not feasible, testing can use combinatorics to maximize coverage while minimizing tests.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Test automation is the use of software (separate from the software being tested) for controlling the execution of tests and comparing actual outcome with predicted.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Test automation supports testing the system under test (SUT) without manual interaction which can lead to faster test execution and testing more often.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Test automation is a key aspect of continuous testing and often for continuous integration and continuous delivery (CI/CD).
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Software testing can be categorized into levels based on how much of the software system is the focus of a test.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Unit testing, a.k.a. component or module testing, is a form of software testing by which isolated source code is tested to validate expected behavior.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Integration testing is a form of software testing in which multiple software components, modules, or services are tested together to verify they work as expected when combined.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] The focus is on testing the interactions and data exchange between integrated parts, rather than testing components in isolation.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] System testing, a.k.a. end-to-end (E2E) testing, is testing conducted on a complete software system.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] There are many approaches to software testing.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Reviews, walkthroughs, or inspections are referred to as static testing, whereas executing programmed code with a given set of test cases is referred to as dynamic testing.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Static testing is often implicit, like proofreading, plus when programming tools/text editors check source code structure or compilers (precompilers) check syntax and data flow as static program analysis.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Dynamic testing takes place when the program itself is run.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Dynamic testing may begin before the program is 100% complete in order to test particular sections of code and are applied to discrete functions or modules.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Typical techniques for these are either using stubs/drivers or execution from a debugger environment.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Static testing involves verification, whereas dynamic testing also involves validation.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Passive testing means verifying the system's behavior without any interaction with the software product.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Contrary to active testing, testers do not provide any test data but look at system logs and traces.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] They mine for patterns and specific behavior in order to make some kind of decisions.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] This is related to offline runtime verification and log analysis.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Exploratory testing is an approach to software testing that is concisely described as simultaneous learning, test design and test execution.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Software testing can often be divided into white-box and black-box.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] These two approaches are used to describe the point of view that the tester takes when designing test cases.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] A hybrid approach called grey-box that includes aspects of both boxes may also be applied to software testing methodology.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] White-box testing (also known as clear box testing, glass box testing, transparent box testing, and structural testing) verifies the internal structures or workings of a program, as opposed to the functionality exposed to the end-user.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] In white-box testing, an internal perspective of the system (the source code), as well as programming skills are used to design test cases.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] The tester chooses inputs to exercise paths through the code and determines the appropriate outputs.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] This is analogous to testing nodes in a circuit, e.g., in-circuit testing (ICT).
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] While white-box testing can be applied at the unit, integration, and system levels of the software testing process, it is usually done at the unit level.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] It can test paths within a unit, paths between units during integration, and between subsystems during a system–level test.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Though this method of test design can uncover many errors or problems, it might not detect unimplemented parts of the specification or missing requirements.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Code coverage tools can evaluate the completeness of a test suite that was created with any method, including black-box testing.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] This allows the software team to examine parts of a system that are rarely tested and ensures that the most important function points have been tested.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] 100% statement coverage ensures that all code paths or branches (in terms of control flow) are executed at least once.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] This is helpful in ensuring correct functionality, but not sufficient since the same code may process different inputs correctly or incorrectly.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Black-box testing (also known as functional testing) describes designing test cases without knowledge of the implementation, without reading the source code.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] The testers are only aware of what the software is supposed to do, not how it does it.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Black-box testing methods include: equivalence partitioning, boundary value analysis, all-pairs testing, state transition tables, decision table testing, fuzz testing, model-based testing, use case testing, exploratory testing, and specification-based testing.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Specification-based testing aims to test the functionality of software according to the applicable requirements.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] This level of testing usually requires thorough test cases to be provided to the tester, who then can simply verify that for a given input, the output value (or behavior), either "is" or "is not" the same as the expected value specified in the test case.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Test cases are built around specifications and requirements, i.e., what the application is supposed to do.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] It uses external descriptions of the software, including specifications, requirements, and designs, to derive test cases.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] These tests can be functional or non-functional, though usually functional.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Specification-based testing may be necessary to assure correct functionality, but it is insufficient to guard against complex or high-risk situations.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Black box testing can be used to any level of testing although usually not at the unit level.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Component interface testing is a variation of black-box testing, with the focus on the data values beyond just the related actions of a subsystem component.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] The practice of component interface testing can be used to check the handling of data passed between various units, or subsystem components, beyond full integration testing between those units.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] The data being passed can be considered as "message packets" and the range or data types can be checked for data generated from one unit and tested for validity before being passed into another unit.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] One option for interface testing is to keep a separate log file of data items being passed, often with a timestamp logged to allow analysis of thousands of cases of data passed between units for days or weeks.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Tests can include checking the handling of some extreme data values while other interface variables are passed as normal values.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Unusual data values in an interface can help explain unexpected performance in the next unit.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] The aim of visual testing is to provide developers with the ability to examine what was happening at the point of software failure by presenting the data in such a way that the developer can easily find the information he or she requires, and the information is expressed clearly.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] At the core of visual testing is the idea that showing someone a problem (or a test failure), rather than just describing it, greatly increases clarity and understanding.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Visual testing, therefore, requires the recording of the entire test process – capturing everything that occurs on the test system in video format.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Output videos are supplemented by real-time tester input via picture-in-a-picture webcam and audio commentary from microphones.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Visual testing provides a number of advantages.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] The quality of communication is increased drastically because testers can show the problem (and the events leading up to it) to the developer as opposed to just describing it, and the need to replicate test failures will cease to exist in many cases.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] The developer will have all the evidence he or she requires of a test failure and can instead focus on the cause of the fault and how it should be fixed.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Ad hoc testing and exploratory testing are important methodologies for checking software integrity because they require less preparation time to implement, while the important bugs can be found quickly.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] In ad hoc testing, where testing takes place in an improvised impromptu way, the ability of the tester(s) to base testing off documented methods and then improvise variations of those tests can result in a more rigorous examination of defect fixes.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] However, unless strict documentation of the procedures is maintained, one of the limits of ad hoc testing is lack of repeatability.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Grey-box testing (American spelling: gray-box testing) involves using knowledge of internal data structures and algorithms for purposes of designing tests while executing those tests at the user, or black-box level.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] The tester will often have access to both "the source code and the executable binary." Grey-box testing may also include reverse engineering (using dynamic code analysis) to determine, for instance, boundary values or error messages.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Manipulating input data and formatting output do not qualify as grey-box, as the input and output are clearly outside of the "black box" that we are calling the system under test.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] This distinction is particularly important when conducting integration testing between two modules of code written by two different developers, where only the interfaces are exposed for the test.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] By knowing the underlying concepts of how the software works, the tester makes better-informed testing choices while testing the software from outside.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Typically, a grey-box tester will be permitted to set up an isolated testing environment with activities, such as seeding a database.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] The tester can observe the state of the product being tested after performing certain actions such as executing SQL statements against the database and then executing queries to ensure that the expected changes have been reflected.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Grey-box testing implements intelligent test scenarios based on limited information.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] This will particularly apply to data type handling, exception handling, and so on.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] With the concept of grey-box testing, this "arbitrary distinction" between black- and white-box testing has faded somewhat.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Installation testing is a type of software testing that verifies that users can successfully install and set up software in its intended environments (e.g., operating systems, computer hardware).
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Most software systems have installation procedures that are needed before they can be used for their main purpose.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Installation testing focuses on these procedures and whether they're sufficient for achieving an installed, usable software system.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Procedures of this kind may involve full or partial upgrades, and install/uninstall processes.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] For example, in the case of a lack of backward compatibility, this can occur because the programmers develop and test software only on the latest version of the target environment, which not all users may be running.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] This results in the unintended consequence that the latest work may not function on earlier versions of the target environment, or on older hardware that earlier versions of the target environment were capable of using.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Sometimes such issues can be fixed by proactively abstracting operating system functionality into a separate program module or library.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Sanity testing determines whether it is reasonable to proceed with further testing.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Smoke testing consists of minimal attempts to operate the software, designed to determine whether there are any basic problems that will prevent it from working at all.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Such tests can be used as build verification test.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Regression testing focuses on finding defects after a major code change has occurred.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Specifically, it seeks to uncover software regressions, as degraded or lost features, including old bugs that have come back.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Such regressions occur whenever software functionality that was previously working correctly, stops working as intended.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Typically, regressions occur as an unintended consequence of program changes, when the newly developed part of the software collides with the previously existing code.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Common methods of regression testing include re-running previous sets of test cases and checking whether previously fixed faults have re-emerged.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] The depth of testing depends on the phase in the release process and the risk of the added features.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] They can either be complete, for changes added late in the release or deemed to be risky, or be very shallow, consisting of positive tests on each feature, if the changes are early in the release or deemed to be of low risk.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Acceptance testing is system-level testing to ensure the software meets customer expectations.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Acceptance testing may be performed at the end or in the middle of a project, including after each completed user story in an agile project.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Tests are frequently grouped into these levels by where they are performed in the software development process, or by the level of specificity of the test.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Sometimes, UAT is performed by the customer, in their environment and on their own hardware.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] OAT is used to conduct operational readiness (prerelease) of a product, service or system as part of a quality management system.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] OAT is a common type of non-functional software testing, used mainly in software development and software maintenance projects.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] This type of testing focuses on the operational readiness of the system to be supported, or to become part of the production environment.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Hence, it is also known as operational readiness testing (ORT) or operations readiness and assurance (OR&A) testing.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Functional testing within OAT is limited to those tests that are required to verify the *non-functional* aspects of the system.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] In addition, the software testing should ensure that the portability of the system, as well as working as expected, does not also damage or partially corrupt its operating environment or cause other processes within that environment to become inoperative.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Contractual acceptance testing is performed based on the contract's acceptance criteria defined during the agreement of the contract, while regulatory acceptance testing is performed based on the relevant regulations to the software product.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Both of these two tests can be performed by users or independent testers.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Regulation acceptance testing sometimes involves the regulatory agencies auditing the test results.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Alpha testing is simulated or actual operational testing by potential users/customers or an independent test team at the developers' site.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Alpha testing is often employed for off-the-shelf software as a form of internal acceptance testing before the software goes to beta testing.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Beta testing comes after alpha testing and can be considered a form of external user acceptance testing.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Versions of the software, known as beta versions, are released to a limited audience outside of the programming team known as beta testers.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] The software is released to groups of people so that further testing can ensure the product has few faults or bugs.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Beta versions can be made available to the open public to increase the feedback field to a maximal number of future users and to deliver value earlier, for an extended or even indefinite period of time (perpetual beta).
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Functional testing refers to activities that verify a specific action or function of the code.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] These are usually found in the code requirements documentation, although some development methodologies work from use cases or user stories.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Non-functional testing refers to aspects of the software that may not be related to a specific function or user action, such as scalability or other performance, behavior under certain constraints, or security.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Testing will determine the breaking point, the point at which extremes of scalability or performance leads to unstable execution.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Non-functional requirements tend to be those that reflect the quality of the product, particularly in the context of the suitability perspective of its users.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Continuous testing is the process of executing automated tests as part of the software delivery pipeline to obtain immediate feedback on the business risks associated with a software release candidate.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Continuous testing includes the validation of both functional requirements and non-functional requirements; the scope of testing extends from validating bottom-up requirements or user stories to assessing the system requirements associated with overarching business goals.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Destructive testing attempts to cause the software or a sub-system to fail.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] It verifies whether the software functions properly when it receives invalid or unexpected inputs, thereby assessing the robustness of input validation and error-management routines.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Software fault injection, in the form of fuzzing, is an example of failure testing.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Various commercial non-functional testing tools are linked from the software fault injection page; there are also numerous open-source and free software tools available that perform destructive testing.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Performance testing is generally executed to determine how a system or sub-system performs in terms of responsiveness and stability under a particular workload.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] It can also serve to investigate, measure, validate or verify other quality attributes of the system, such as scalability, reliability and resource usage.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] There is little agreement on what the specific goals of performance testing are.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] The terms load testing, performance testing, scalability testing, and volume testing, are often used interchangeably.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Real-time software systems have strict timing constraints.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] To test if timing constraints are met, real-time testing is used.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Usability testing is to check if the user interface is easy to use and understand.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] It is concerned mainly with the use of the application.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] This is not a kind of testing that can be automated; actual human users are needed, being monitored by skilled UI designers.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Usability testing can use structured models to check how well an interface works.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] The Stanton, Theofanos, and Joshi (2015) model looks at user experience, and the Al-Sharafat and Qadoumi (2016) model is for expert evaluation, helping to assess usability in digital applications.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Accessibility testing is done to ensure that the software is accessible to persons with disabilities.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Security testing is essential for software that processes confidential data to prevent system intrusion by hackers.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Testing for internationalization and localization validates that the software can be used with different languages and geographic regions.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] The process of pseudolocalization is used to test the ability of an application to be translated to another language, and make it easier to identify when the localization process may introduce new bugs into the product.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Globalization testing verifies that the software is adapted for a new culture, such as different currencies or time zones.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Actual translation to human languages must be tested, too.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Development testing is a software development process that involves the synchronized application of a broad spectrum of defect prevention and detection strategies in order to reduce software development risks, time, and costs.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] It is performed by the software developer or engineer during the construction phase of the software development lifecycle.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Development testing aims to eliminate construction errors before code is promoted to other testing; this strategy is intended to increase the quality of the resulting software as well as the efficiency of the overall development process.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Depending on the organization's expectations for software development, development testing might include static code analysis, data flow analysis, metrics analysis, peer code reviews, unit testing, code coverage analysis, traceability, and other software testing practices.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] A/B testing is a method of running a controlled experiment to determine if a proposed change is more effective than the current approach.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Customers are routed to either a current version (control) of a feature, or to a modified version (treatment) and data is collected to determine which version is better at achieving the desired outcome.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Concurrent or concurrency testing assesses the behaviour and performance of software and systems that use concurrent computing, generally under normal usage conditions.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Typical problems this type of testing will expose are deadlocks, race conditions and problems with shared memory/resource handling.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] In software testing, conformance testing verifies that a product performs according to its specified standards.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Compilers, for instance, are extensively tested to determine whether they meet the recognized standard for that language.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] For example, every output from a serialization function should be accepted by the corresponding deserialization function, and every output from a sort function should be a monotonically increasing list containing exactly the same elements as its input.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Property testing libraries allow the user to control the strategy by which random inputs are constructed, to ensure coverage of degenerate cases, or inputs featuring specific patterns that are needed to fully exercise aspects of the implementation under test.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Property testing is also sometimes known as "generative testing" or "QuickCheck testing" since it was introduced and popularized by the Haskell library QuickCheck.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Metamorphic testing (MT) is a property-based software testing technique, which can be an effective approach for addressing the test oracle problem and test case generation problem.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] The test oracle problem is the difficulty of determining the expected outcomes of selected test cases or to determine whether the actual outputs agree with the expected outcomes.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] VCR testing, also known as "playback testing" or "record/replay" testing, is a testing technique for increasing the reliability and speed of regression tests that involve a component that is slow or unreliable to communicate with, often a third-party API outside of the tester's control.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] It involves making a recording ("cassette") of the system's interactions with the external component, and then replaying the recorded interactions as a substitute for communicating with the external system on subsequent runs of the test.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] The technique was popularized in web development by the Ruby library vcr.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] It is often used in the context of distributed systems, service-oriented software architectures, and microservices.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Since the early 2020s, artificial intelligence has increasingly been integrated into software testing workflows.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] AI-driven testing methods automate the creation of test cases, dynamically adapt to changes, and leverage machine learning to identify high-risk areas of the codebase — an approach that enhances regression testing efficiency while expanding overall test coverage.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] A key development is **self-healing test automation**, in which automated tests automatically detect and adapt to changes in a user interface without human intervention.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Studies of AI-driven test automation across over 3,600 grey literature sources identified self-healing test scripts as one of the most common AI solutions in practice.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] A case study presented at the 2023 International Conference on Information Management and Technology (ICIMTech) found that integrating shift-left testing into an agile development methodology over one year measurably reduced the number of bugs reaching production.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] In an organization, testers may be in a separate team from the rest of the software development team or they may be integrated into one team.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Software testing can also be performed by non-dedicated software testers.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] In the 1980s, the term *software tester* started to be used to denote a separate profession.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Notable software testing roles and titles include: *test manager*, *test lead*, *test analyst*, *test designer*, *tester*, *automation developer*, and *test administrator*.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Organizations that develop software, perform testing differently, but there are common patterns.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] In waterfall development, testing is generally performed after the code is completed, but before the product is shipped to the customer.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] This practice often results in the testing phase being used as a project buffer to compensate for project delays, thereby compromising the time devoted to testing.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Some contend that the waterfall process allows for testing to start when the development project starts and to be a continuous process until the project finishes.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Agile software development commonly involves testing while the code is being written and organizing teams with both programmers and testers and with team members performing both programming and testing.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] One agile practice, test-driven software development (TDD), is a way of unit testing such that unit-level testing is performed while writing the product code.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Test code is updated as new features are added and failure conditions are discovered (bugs fixed).
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Commonly, the unit test code is maintained with the project code, integrated in the build process, and run on each build and as part of regression testing.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Goals of this continuous integration is to support development and reduce defects.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] Even in organizations that separate teams by programming and testing functions, many often have the programmers perform unit testing.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] The sample below is common for waterfall development.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p01] The same activities are commonly found in other development models, but might be described differently.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] The terms verification and validation are commonly used interchangeably in the industry; it is also common to see these two terms defined with contradictory definitions.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] Verification is the process of evaluating a system or component to determine whether the products of a given development phase satisfy the conditions imposed at the start of that phase.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] Validation is the process of evaluating a system or component during or at the end of the development process to determine whether it satisfies specified requirements.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] Verification is confirmation by examination and through provision of objective evidence that specified requirements have been fulfilled.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] Validation is confirmation by examination and through provision of objective evidence that the requirements for a specific intended use or application have been fulfilled.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] The contradiction is caused by the use of the concepts of requirements and specified requirements but with different meanings.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] In the case of IEEE standards, the specified requirements, mentioned in the definition of validation, are the set of problems, needs and wants of the stakeholders that the software must solve and satisfy.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] Such requirements are documented in a Software Requirements Specification (SRS).
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] And, the products mentioned in the definition of verification, are the output artifacts of every phase of the software development process.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] These products are, in fact, specifications such as Architectural Design Specification, Detailed Design Specification, etc.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] The SRS is also a specification, but it cannot be verified (at least not in the sense used here – more on this subject below).
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] But, for the ISO 9000, the specified requirements are the set of specifications, as just mentioned above, that must be verified.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] A specification, as previously explained, is the product of a software development process phase that receives another specification as input.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] A specification is verified successfully when it correctly implements its input specification.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] All the specifications can be verified except the SRS because it is the first one (it can be validated, though).
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] An example scenario be that the Design Specification must implement the SRS, and the Construction phase artifacts must implement the Design Specification.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] So, when these words are defined in common terms, the apparent contradiction disappears.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] Both the SRS and the software must be validated.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] The SRS can be validated statically by consulting with the stakeholders.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] Nevertheless, running some partial implementation of the software or a prototype of any kind (dynamic testing) and obtaining positive feedback from them, can further increase the certainty that the SRS is correctly formulated.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] On the other hand, the software, as a final and running product (not its artifacts and documents, including the source code) must be validated dynamically with the stakeholders by executing the software and having them to try it.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] Some might argue that, for SRS, the input is the words of stakeholders and, therefore, SRS validation is the same as SRS verification.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] Thinking this way is not advisable as it only causes more confusion.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] It is better to think of verification as a process involving a formal and technical input document.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] In some organizations, software testing is part of a software quality assurance (SQA) process.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] In SQA, software process specialists and auditors are concerned with the software development process rather than just the artifacts such as documentation, code and systems.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] They examine and change the software engineering process itself to reduce the number of faults that end up in the delivered software: the so-called defect rate.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] What constitutes an acceptable defect rate depends on the nature of the software; a flight simulator video game would have much higher defect tolerance than software for an actual airplane.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] Although there are close links with SQA, testing departments often exist independently, and there may be no SQA function in some companies.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] Software testing is an activity to investigate software under test in order to provide quality-related information to stakeholders.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] By contrast, QA (quality assurance) is the implementation of policies and procedures intended to prevent defects from reaching customers.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] Quality measures include such topics as correctness, completeness, security and ISO/IEC 9126 requirements such as capability, reliability, efficiency, portability, maintainability, compatibility, and usability.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] There are a number of frequently used software metrics, or measures, which are used to assist in determining the state of the software or the adequacy of the testing.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] A software testing process can produce several artifacts.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] The actual artifacts produced are a factor of the software development model used, stakeholder and organisational needs.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] A test plan is a document detailing the approach that will be taken for intended test activities.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] The plan may include aspects such as objectives, scope, processes and procedures, personnel requirements, and contingency plans.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] The test plan could come in the form of a single plan that includes all test types (like an acceptance or system test plan) and planning considerations, or it may be issued as a master test plan that provides an overview of more than one detailed test plan (a plan of a plan).
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] A test plan can be, in some cases, part of a wide "test strategy" which documents overall testing approaches, which may itself be a master test plan or even a separate artifact.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] In software development, a traceability matrix (TM) is a document, usually in the form of a table, used to assist in determining the completeness of a relationship by correlating any two baselined documents using a many-to-many relationship comparison.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] It is often used with high-level requirements (these often consist of marketing requirements) and detailed requirements of the product to the matching parts of high-level design, detailed design, test plan, and test cases.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] A test case normally consists of a unique identifier, requirement references from a design specification, preconditions, events, a series of steps (also known as actions) to follow, input, output, expected result, and the actual result.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] Clinically defined, a test case is an input and an expected result.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] This can be as terse as "for condition x your derived result is y", although normally test cases describe in more detail the input scenario and what results might be expected.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] It can occasionally be a series of steps (but often steps are contained in a separate test procedure that can be exercised against multiple test cases, as a matter of economy) but with one expected result or expected outcome.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] The optional fields are a test case ID, test step, or order of execution number, related requirement(s), depth, test category, author, and check boxes for whether the test is automatable and has been automated.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] Larger test cases may also contain prerequisite states or steps, and descriptions.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] A test case should also contain a place for the actual result.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] These steps can be stored in a word processor document, spreadsheet, database, or other common repositories.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] In a database system, you may also be able to see past test results, who generated the results, and what system configuration was used to generate those results.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] These past results would usually be stored in a separate table.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] A test script is a procedure or programming code that replicates user actions.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] Initially, the term was derived from the product of work created by automated regression test tools.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] A test case will be a baseline to create test scripts using a tool or a program.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] In software development, a test suite, less commonly known as a validation suite, is a collection of test cases that are intended to be used to test a software program to show that it has some specified set of behaviors.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] A test suite often contains detailed instructions or goals for each collection of test cases and information on the system configuration to be used during testing.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] A group of test cases may also contain prerequisite states or steps and descriptions of the following tests.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] In most cases, multiple sets of values or data are used to test the same functionality of a particular feature.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] All the test values and changeable environmental components are collected in separate files and stored as test data.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] It is also useful to provide this data to the client and with the product or a project.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] There are techniques to generate Test data.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] The software, tools, samples of data input and output, and configurations are all referred to collectively as a test harness.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] A test run is a collection of test cases or test suites that the user is executing and comparing the expected with the actual results.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] Once complete, a report or all executed tests may be generated.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] Several certification programs exist to support the professional aspirations of software testers and quality assurance specialists.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] A few practitioners argue that the testing field is not ready for certification, as mentioned in the controversy section.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] is so expensive relative to its value that it should be used sparingly.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] The test automation then can be considered as a way to capture and implement the requirements.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] As a general rule, the larger the system and the greater the complexity, the greater the ROI in test automation.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] Also, the investment in tools and expertise can be amortized over multiple projects with the right level of knowledge sharing within an organization.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] Significant opposition has formed out of the ranks of the context-driven school of software testing about the ISO 29119 standard.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] Professional testing associations, such as the International Society for Software Testing, have attempted to have the standard withdrawn.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] No certification now offered actually requires the applicant to show their ability to test software.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] No certification is based on a widely accepted body of knowledge.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] Certification itself cannot measure an individual's productivity, their skill, or practical knowledge, and cannot guarantee their competence, or professionalism as a tester.
[src:hypothesis-property/software-testing-p02] There are opposing views on the applicability of studies used to show the relative expense of fixing defects depending on their introduction and detection.
